John Edward: Essential Language Skills for the Citizens of the World
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continues in 2018 with an additional set of outstanding test scores, reinforced by individual and group success in sports, arts, music, and other areas of the community.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, for a career in which they will choose and belong as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that is able to design and implement a customized curriculum, we find that modern languages continue to gain popularity as a sought-after field of study in the school.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a person in a language they understand, it goes into his head.
If you talk to a man in his own language, it goes into his heart."
It's an important reminder that we can't just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the latest tests this year, you can see that languages are at the top of tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A score.
The data collected from the 74 schools that members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students achieved a high A score in Mandarin, as did 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish.
These data show that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and adolescents will no doubt need in the future.
Today the field of languages as a subject of choice is considered to be on the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the British Council on Employment and Skills found that of the reasons employers noted for Cody to fill vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Thus, to an increasing extent, language skills are becoming an essential necessity to prepare students for careers in the future.
Faced with the rise in language requirements for future job opportunities, these skills are essential in a world of globalization.
No matter which career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a significant advantage in the future thanks to this ability that lasts a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically position a person in an advantageous position over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language at a sufficient level for conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit number of speakers, 15 percent.
This is why it is important to invest in teaching languages to children today.
Knowledge of many languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different as to the languages taught in it.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will learn languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking forward to the 1920s, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever the child's area of interest, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in the independent schools, with a team of teachers specializing in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, in any foreseeable future.
One cannot deny today, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this fact should be expressed in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer these levels of choice, diversity and excellence to the children of Scotland.
That's the order of the hour.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools.
