World Wide Web Inventor Plans to Start New Web to Overcome Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a start-up company to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of the man who has become a legend in the technology world, is a company that will develop Solid, Berners-Lee's open source platform.
The Solid platform allows its users to choose where their data will be stored and who people will be allowed access to the different data types.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is "control of the world."
"We have to do it now," he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create a "personal online database" or POD.
The repository will be able to include a contact list, lists of operations to perform, a schedule, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
Imagine that Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify would all be available in one browser at the same time.
What distinguishes the personal online database is that the user alone is the one who decides who can access the information and what kind of information can be accessed.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
According to John Bruce, CEO of the company, Inrupt will find the appropriate resources, process and capabilities to help make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, a team of several developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer code programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers from around the world will be able to create distributed apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team do not discuss with Facebook and Google their agreement or refusal to introduce a complete change, which would cause a complete and overnight reversal in all of their business models.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post published in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission "is to provide commercial energy and an environmental system to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network being built at Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the face of the Internet when he founded the Network Standards Organization, W3C at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in discussing net neutrality.
Even during Inrupt's launch, Berners-Lee will continue to serve as founder and director of the W3C, the Web Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm particularly optimistic about the next era of the network," Berners-Lee added.
