He wanted to prove that he was "something," he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they eventually found out what his sexual orientation was.
The man who won the Olympic bronze medal twice became a mediated leader of the LGBT community campaign and used his participation in the Commonwealth Games in Australia this year to call on other countries to legalize homosexuality.
He spoke openly on the subject because he felt lucky to have been given the opportunity to live openly and without consequences and wanted to give others "hope".
The triple winner of the World Series said that falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "took me by surprise".
