The acceptance of Germany's new warship has been postponed once again.
Germany's new fleet frigate was to be accepted in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War-era warships, but it was postponed for at least a year, due to faulty systems and reduced cost, local media reported.
The acceptance of Rheinland-Pfalz, the lead ship on the new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate line, was now postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a report by the newspaper Dee Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but worrying issues after the supply shut down the unfolding of the ambitious project.
All four of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class cruises, which the Navy ordered back in 2007, will replace the older Bremen-class frigates.
It is expected that they will include a powerful cannon, anti-aircraft and anti-ship missile batteries as well as stealth technologies, such as acoustic signatures, infrared and reduced radar.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the newest frigates can be deployed for up to two years away from home ports.
However, repeated delays mean that the innovative ships – which are supposed to allow Germany to send troops overseas – will become obsolete by the time they enter service, Dee Zeit noted.
The unfortunate frigate F125 made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to accept the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
Not much is known about the reasons behind the recall, but German media cited a number of critical "software and hardware deficiencies" that made the warship useless for use in combat missions.
The software deficiencies were particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class naval vessels would be operated by about 120 sailors - about half of the crew used in the older Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it was discovered that the ship has a dramatic excess weight that reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add upgrades in the future.
The ship Rheinland-Pfalz weighs 7,000 tons and is twice as heavy as ships of a similar type used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from the faulty software, the price tag of the entire project – which also includes the team training – is also becoming a problem.
It has reportedly reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) – beyond the original 2.2 billion euros.
The problems that fascinate the newest frigates are becoming especially important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the Security Committee of the German Parliament, confirmed that today, the Navy "is running out of ships capable of carrying out deployment".
The official source said the problem gained momentum and increased over time, as old ships were decommissioned but not replaced by other vessels.
He expressed his regret that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate could be attached to the Navy.
The National Trust of Scotland listens to the secret life of bats
A new study conducted on a mansion in the Highlands of Scotland aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt their food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The research done by scientists at the National Trust of Scotland will follow common bats and European kites as well as the brown and long-eared Dubenton bats at Inberio Gardens in Worcester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key sites around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
The National Health Service (NHS) staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using manual detectors.
A specialized sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequencies of the bat readings and which of the species is responsible for them.
Next, a map of the living areas will be drawn to create a detailed picture on the order of the landscape, of their patterns of behavior.
Rob Dower, a conservation consultant for the National Trust of Scotland (NTS) hopes the results will reveal which habitats are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of living areas management work, such as creating meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom were significantly reduced during the previous century.
They are under threat from development and construction works, which affect the nesting and loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting may also pose a risk, and this is also true for fly traps and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, bat ears are more useful when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo detection technique to detect insects and identify obstacles to their flight path.
The NTS Foundation, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 760,000 acres of land all over the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has 10 skilled specialists, who regularly conduct surveys, nesting tests and sometimes rescue.
The organization also established the first and only reserve dedicated to bats at the T'Ribb estate in Damparis and Galway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager David Thompson said the estate was the ideal territory for them.
"Here in T'Ribb we have a great area for the bats," he said.
We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and all the appropriate living areas.
But many things are still unknown about the bats, so the work we do here and in other assets will help us understand more what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of testing for finding bats before carrying out maintenance work within the properties, as the unintentional destruction of a single populated nest could destroy up to 400 females and puppies, and may also destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and killing, harassing and interfering with bats or the destruction of their nesting areas are prohibited by law.
Elizabeth Pearl, a Scottish clerk at the Bat Conservancy Foundation, encouraged the public to lend a shoulder and help.
She said: "We have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species we just don't know how their populations are doing."
