Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Sippolo Saipov, suspected of the New York City terror attack that killed eight people - a rare punishment that has not been carried out for a federal crime in the state since 1953.
The 30-year-old Saipov allegedly used a rented home depot truck to carry out a bike-track attack alongside the West Side Highway in southern Manhattan, and ran over pedestrians and cyclists who got in his way in October.
In order to justify the death penalty, prosecutors must prove that Saipov deliberately killed the eight victims and caused serious body injuries, according to the intent statement for the death penalty application, filed in the Southern District of New York.
According to the court's document, the death penalty may be sought on these two counts.
Weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury slapped Sipov with a charge of 22 counts, including eight counts of murder in aid of extortion, commonly used by federal prosecutors in cases of organized crime, and a charge of violence and the destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack demanded "significant planning in advance and deliberately first," prosecutors said, describing the manner in which Saipov carried out the attack as "humiliating, cruel and sickly."
"Saipolo Habibulevich Saifov has caused harm, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicolas Calaves, Ann-Laur Decid, Darren Drake, Ariel Arlig, Hernan Ferrucci, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Paniko," the statement read.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
The last time the Southern District of New York sued for the death penalty in a case occurred a decade ago.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of the murder of two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was executed in a federal case in New York City was in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple executed after their conviction in a conspiracy for espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years before.
The two Rosenbergs were executed in an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court documents, Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, did not express remorse in the days and months following the attack.
He stated to investigators that he felt good about his actions, police said.
Saipov told authorities that he was inspired by the attack after watching ISIS videos on his phone, according to the indictment.
