He claimed he was innocent in response to the 22-count indictment.
David Patton, one of the federal defense attorneys representing Saipov, said they were "disappointed of course" by the prosecution's decision.
"We think that the decision to seek the death penalty instead of accepting an admission of guilt that would lead to life imprisonment without the possibility of release will only prolong the duration of the trauma of these events on all those involved," Patton said.
Seipov's defense team had previously asked prosecutors not to seek the death penalty.
