How the U.S.-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The opening salvos of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and although the battle is far from over, a rift between the countries could benefit Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, fired the opening shot earlier this year when he levied a tax on important Chinese exports including solar, steel and aluminum collectors.
The most significant escalation occurred this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion worth of goods ($150 million), imposing taxes on virtually half of the goods imported to the U.S. from China.
Beijing responded with the same coin each time, and recently raised rates by five to ten percent on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has pledged to strike back on every blow by the United States, and it is unlikely that the world's second-largest economy will surrender in the near future.
A request from Washington to retract would mean a capitulation to its demands, but a public bow to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts say that if Beijing succeeds in getting things right, the pressures from the trade war with the U.S. may positively support China in the long run, reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions for the start of an economic spiral in each of the countries is actually much more dangerous than previously expected," said Abigail Grace, a research partner focused on Asia, in the New American Security think tank.
Syria 'ready' to return refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for aid to rebuild the country that has been destroyed in a long war that has lasted for over seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Muallem said the conditions in the country were improving.
"Today the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the war on terror," he said.
The government continues to restore the areas destroyed by the terrorists in order to restore the situation to normal.
All conditions now exist for the return of refugees of their own free will to the country they left because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures, aimed at harming their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to UN estimates, over 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Muallem said the Syrian regime would welcome assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that the regime would not receive conditional aid or assistance from countries that funded the rebels.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris.
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated the U.S. team with a final score of 16.5 - 10.5 at the La Golf National track outside Paris, France.
The U.S. has so far lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the crown again when Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points it needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Michaelson, who struggled for almost the entire tournament, sent his T-string into the water on the 16th hole of Par-3, losing the game against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari has polished all his rounds, becoming one of the four players to reach 5-0-0 since the start of the tournament in the current formation, in 1979.
American player Jordan Spith was defeated 5th and 4th by the lowest ranked player on the European team, Thorbjorn Olsen of Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, the top ranked player in the world, lost 2 and 1 to England's Ian Falter, which may be the last time he will play in the Ryder Cup.
With a record eight participations in the Ryder Cup, Spanish Sergio Garcia became the European player with the highest number of wins in tournaments with 25.5 career points.
"I don't usually cry but today I can't resist.
It's been a tough year.
So I'm grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so happy, so happy to have the trophy back.
It's a team, and I'm glad I could help," Garcia said excitedly after the European victory.
He passes the torch to his compatriot John Ram who defeated American legend Tiger Woods 2 and 1 in the singles game on Sunday.
"The tremendous pride I feel, defeating Tiger Woods, which I watched growing up," said 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost all four games in France and his record now stands at 13-21-3, peaking at the Ryder Cup in his career.
This is odd statistics from one of the best players of all time, who has won 14 important titles, with only Jack Nicklaus in front of him.
The U.S. team struggled throughout the weekend to find its way through the lawns, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Pineau who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
Team captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance, "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
There was a moment this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We failed.
Good for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We'll regroup, I'll work with the American Professional Golf Association and our Ryder Cup committee and we'll move on.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be captain.
The hat needs to be taken off.
We've been defeated."
Update on the Red Tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in a portion of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC Commission, more diffuse flowering conditions have been reported in the provinces of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – indicating decreasing concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends about 130 miles from the coastline, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in several locations smaller than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pascoe County.
Medium concentrations on or off the coast of Pinellas County were reported last week, low to medium concentrations off the shoreline of Hillsborough County, background concentrations up to high concentrations in Manati County, background concentrations up to high concentrations on the shoreline or opposite the coast of Sarasota County, background concentrations up to middle concentrations in Charlotte County, background concentrations up to high concentrations on the shoreline or across the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations.
Reports of respiratory stimuli continue from Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory stimuli have been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
